SENATE BILL DRS45074-ML-59
Short Title: Theft of Temporary Housing During Emergency. (Public)
Sponsors: Senator Alexander (Primary Sponsor).
Referred to:
1 A BILL TO BE ENTITLED
2 AN ACT TO SPECIFY THE PUNISHMENT FOR ENTERING THE PREMISES OF
3 ANOTHER PERSON WITHOUT LEGAL JUSTIFICATION IN A COUNTY LOCATED
4 IN AN EMERGENCY AREA DURING A STATE OF EMERGENCY AND TAKING OR
5 DAMAGING THE PERSON'S TEMPORARY HOUSING.
6 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
7 SECTION 1. G.S. 14-288.6 reads as rewritten:
8 "§ 14-288.6. Looting; trespass during emergency.
9 (a) Any person who enters upon the premises of another without legal justification when
10 the usual security of property is not effective due to the occurrence or aftermath of riot,
11 insurrection, invasion, storm, fire, explosion, flood, collapse, or other disaster or calamity is
12 guilty of a Class 1 misdemeanor of trespass during an emergency.
13 (b) Any person who commits the crime of trespass during emergency and, without legal
14 justification, obtains or exerts control over, damages, ransacks, or destroys the property of
15 another is guilty of the felony of looting and shall be punished as a Class H felon.
16 (b1) Unless the conduct is covered under some other provision of law providing greater
17 punishment, any person who (i) enters the premises of another without legal justification, in a
18 county located in an emergency area during a state of emergency, and (ii) without legal
19 justification obtains or exerts control over, damages, ransacks, or destroys the temporary housing
20 of another is guilty of a Class F felony. The following definitions apply to this subsection:
21 (1) Emergency area. – As defined in G.S. 166A-19.3.
22 (2) State of emergency. – As defined in G.S. 166A-19.3.
23 (3) Temporary housing. – Any of the following:
24 a. A tent, trailer, mobile home, or any other structure being used for
25 human shelter which is designed to be transportable and is not attached
26 to the ground, to another structure, or to any utility system on the same
27 premises.
28 b. A vehicular unit being used as temporary living quarters.
29 c. Any equipment used to transport or deliver a structure or vehicle
30 described in sub-subdivision a. or b. of this subdivision.
31 d. Any item attached, affixed, or connected to, or intended to be attached,
32 connected, or affixed to, a structure or vehicle described in
33 sub-subdivision a. or b. of this subdivision to provide air conditioning,
34 heating, or a source of power for the structure or vehicle.
*DRS45074-ML-59*

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (c) Any person whose person or property is injured by reason of a violation of this section
2 may sue for and recover from the violator three times the actual damages sustained, as well as
3 court costs and attorneys' fees."
4 SECTION 2. This act becomes effective December 1, 2025, and applies to offenses
5 committed on or after that date.
